The Oceanic White Tip shark, one of my favorite sharks to swim with, also the shark responsible for more human deaths than any other shark.  The reason for this is they cruise the open ocean and can go weeks at a time without food.  So in the case of shipwrecks they are typically the first to show up, investing any disturbance at the surface.  The Navy used to teach sailors to kick and splash and make a lot of noise if they saw a shark, which is exactly opposite of what should be done.  Needless to say that didn't work well.  An incredibly beautiful, cunning and curious shark.
.
.
.
#oceanicwhitetip #shark #naturephotography #marinelife #oceanphotography

If your interested in an experience like this send me a DM, I'll be putting dates together for future retreats.

Usually I post the exciting things we see while diving, unfortunately the past few weeks have just seeing more and more plastic, trash and tangled fishing gear, dying coral, white tip reef sharks with hooks embedded in their mouths, turtles with tumors from nitrogen run off from fertilizer.  It's devastating the impact humans are having on the ocean.  There was a study that by 2050 there will be more plastic than fish in the ocean, around heavily populated areas like Oahu this is already becoming the case.  We need stronger regulations, and more diligent people to protect this vital resource before it's too late.  It's so disheartening to dive and have this be the normal scene every day.
.
.
.
.
#plasticfree #protecttheocean #nopollution 
#ocean #oceanlife

This video is a great example of how the color spectrum changes as depth is increased.  As we dive down red is lost at about 15ft, orange is lost at about 25ft, followed by yellow at 35feet, green at 65ft and finally blue at about 200ft.  Often I get asked how deep a freediver has to be able to dive to get good pictures, many times the lighting, and coloration is the best within the first 20ft, after that we have to adjust for color loss and darkening water.

Happy Earth Day 2023.  For most of the population the ocean is the vast unknown, it's mysterious, scary, unlimited, untouched but also out of sight out of mind.  The truth is it's an area with finite resources, with fragile ecosystems, sensitive to changes in temperature, pH, sensitive to a species being taken out of the food chain.  Whales, dolphins and sharks are now competing with ocean tankers with nets miles long taking bait fish, reefs are being destroyed by ocean trawlers who scrape the bottom in an attempt to catch shrimp but end up with 95percent other species which dies unnecessarily.  I believe if the same amount of devastation was happening on land and visibility was increased people would be appalled and put and end to the destructive practices.  However for many it's unknown where their pets food, cosmetics, seafood etc comes from or how it's obtained.  We need to continue to bring awareness to this and put an end to destructive practices!
.
.
.

#earthday #earthday2023 #savetheocean #oceanconservation

Happy World Ocean Day!  Here are a collection of images from the last few years that demonstrate some of the beauty I have been fortunate enough to witness.  Today we celebrate the immense beauty and power of our world's oceans, but unfortunately the oceans are in trouble and we must take drastic measures to protect it before it's too late.  I have personally witnessed the damage from commercial fishing, dying reefs, plastic pollution, decreasing fish populations and pollution from contaminated ground water. 
While heading out for a dive in Hawaii I ran into an older spearfisherman.  He told me that in the '70s and '80s they would go out for a few hours and fill their coolers with plenty of fish, he said now he doesn't even bother fishing because the fish numbers are down so much.
In Italy I had a chance to dive in the clear waters, but asked one of the dive masters if there's any marine life and he said most of fish have been killed a long time ago due to overfishing, it was sad to see such an empty area of the ocean.  We must make changes before the damage becomes irreversible!

#happyworldoceanday #worldoceanday #savetheocean #ocean #oceanday #saveourseas #oceanconservation

While cave diving yesterday a friend and I noticed a turtle hiding in the back of the cave, as it started to swim I noticed braided fishing line wrapped tight around its neck and flippers causing its left flipper and neck to have restricted movement.  I knew as this turtle continues to grow this line could be a death sentence.  We followed it for a bit and I took an opportunity to dive down and attempt to cut the line, on the first attempt I was able to cut a few of the lines but there were many more wrapped tightly.  After cutting my finger on the sharp line and several more drops we were finally successful in freeing the turtle from the line.  It's sad scenes like this are all too common, humans impact is so devastating to the ocean.  If your a fisherman be sure to remove all line from any animals you may catch as bycatch.  Let's all do our part to protect what we have left.
.
.
.
#savetheturtles #marineconservation #protectourwildlife #protectourmarinelife #marinelife #oceanlove #savetheocean

Here @eye_sirison keeps a close watch over @erikdonathan as he returns to the surface from a 50meter training dive.  As a trained freediver she knows the signs and symptoms of a diver who is struggling, she knows how to time her dive to meet him as he come up from the depths, she repositions herself to gain eye contact, and she knows how to rescue him if he were to have a loss of motor control or blackout. 

Learning these protocols and procedures and adhering to them can save a life, and has saved mine in the past due to an attentive dive buddy who was paying close attention and knew the rescue procedures.  Recently we had two tragic deaths of freedivers on Oahu, while we don't know the exact circumstances it could have potentially been prevented.  Taking a freedive class isn't just learning how to hold your breath longer, or dive deeper, it's primarily learning the safety associated with freediving and spearfishing.  It's learning dive protocols, timing of depth diving, proper buddy distancing and rescue techniques in case of an emergency.  I highly recommend anyone getting into Freediving to take a class from a certified instructor and to follow safety rules, it could save your life.

Here a Manta Ray glides through the bubbles from a group of freedivers below, a Blue shark visits us at sunset, a turtle scratches it's flipper and dolphins play.  It's a collection of images I found while going through photos to submit to Prints for Maui, a fundraiser put together by @mattaleong for photographers from all over Hawaii to help aid the victims of the wildfires.  Maui was the first Hawaiian Island I lived and worked on, it's where I got my start with photography, where I fell in love with diving and my first interactions dolphins, sharks and turtles.  It's also where I experienced the gracious Hawaiian people, the aloha spirit and the tight community that helps each other out.  The amazing response from the community has been incredible to witness, but the lack of response from the federal government is appalling.  Let's keep working together to help the beautiful people and island of Maui.  Whether it's this fundraiser or any others that assist local families.
To purchase prints for Maui see the link in my bio.

Green Sea Turtle coming up for a breath at sunset.  Sea Turtles can hold their breath for approximately 45 to 60 minutes and even longer when they are resting.  During typical activity they usually dive for 4-10 minutes.  Us free divers can learn a lot from turtles. Their slow nonchalant movement, resting at the bottom and relaxed surfacing protocol allow them to conserve oxygen and keep their heart rate low.  They are incredibly fast swimmers when they need to be, but rarely do they use their speed.
.

A Humpback whale calf takes a quick breath while cuddling with mom.  Adult humpback whales can hold their breath 20 to 40 minutes, but the calf needs to come up for air every 3 to 8 minutes.  Often mom will rest near the surface allowing the calf quick access to air.  On one of these occasions calf took interest in us and circled us for 15 minutes playfully looking us in the eye and doing circles around our group.  These gentle giants are so incredible to witness underwater, but we must continue to protect them and give them plenty of space.
*In this video the linear zoom tool was used in post production to zoom in, we kept our distance and allowed mom and calf to rest without interrupting them.
.
.
.
#humpbackwhale #moorea #whale 
#natureisbeautiful #underwatervideo #freedive

The last day of the trip we came across an area where the surface seemed to be brimming with life, large splashes, small splashes, in every direction there were animals playing.  We quietly slipped in the water and we were greeted to this scene, three Humpback whales swimming with a large pod of Pilot whales.  Picture two is from the day prior where we witnessed humpback whales swimming with rough tooth dolphins.  These interspecies interactions are incredible to witness, but we were perplexed as to why they interact, if it's purely for social interaction or some other reason.

As I spend another year around the sun I look back on experiences like these with incredible gratitude, the ability to witness scenes like these make me feel so blessed, but also inspire me to do my part to protect the ocean as much as possible so future generations are still able to have experiences like these.
.
.
.
#marinelife #savetheocean #humpbackwhale #pilotwhale #underwaterphotography

A watchful Humpback whale mother making a slow pass as the calf stays protected below.  Ocean life doesn't seem to know what to make of these akwards swimming humans that bob along at the surface, so we are unknown to them.  Our actions dictate how these animals perceive us, when our group kept it's distance, stayed still and acted as unthreatening as possible the mother and calf would show curiosity and do a close pass, seemingly investigating us further.  However other groups we notice who would swim quickly towards the whales and not give them space, would scare the whales away as they could have been perceived as a threat.  Such an incredible scene to witness.

I've been shark diving all over the world with many species of sharks.  Each type of shark has a very different personality and style of hunting.  Shark diving at night with bull sharks was a new and incredible experience for me.  We had ten plus bull sharks and one quick pass from a hammerhead sharks during the dive.  On high alert throughout the dive we kept watch out for each other and any bulls sneaking in behind the lit area.  The lights illuminated the sharks and made for some incredible, interesting and different images.  Which is your favorite?

Thank You to @x__e__l__a__expeditions for getting us out and keeping us safe.
